      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "This perspective is in line with the American Founding Fathers' vision of the public sphere, as articulated by John Locke and members of the Enlightenment. The idea is that just as a public square should not excuse any content due to its offensive nature, nor should private property owners attempt to regulate who enters their space. The notion is that since the internet is considered a genuinely public forum, it is largely exempt from restrictions for free speech and expression.",
      "source": "target",
